    type='think',
    think='Let me now analyze what I\'ve found and prepare my review report.\n\n
Key findings:\n\n**Blocking issues:**\n1. **UIAlert hide() animation duration mi
smatch with PRD-004**: PRD-004 5.15 specifies hide() duration=200ms, but code us
es `UITweens.fade.duration` which is 150ms.\n2. **UISegmentedControl still has `
id` in one place**: `BuildingSelector.ts` uses `onSelect` which still exists in 
`UIList.ts` but `UISegmentedControl` changed from `selectedId` to `selectedIndex
`. Need to check if any other files still reference the old API.\n3. **Tests can
not run**: vitest not found / node_modules missing - I can\'t verify test pass/f
ail status.\n\nWait, let me re-check. `BuildingSelector.ts` diff shows it still 
uses `onSelect` on `UIList`, not `UISegmentedControl`. `UIList` still has `onSel
ect` - that\'s fine since `UIList` wasn\'t renamed. The `UISegmentedControl` mig
ration seems correct for its own callers.\n\nActually, looking at the `export de
fault` grep results - the city-builder files still have `export default`. The PR
only removed `export default` from `src/ui/` files but not from `city-builder/ui
/`. The PRD-004 9.2 says "`city-builder/ui/` 中的旧组件全部迁移使用新版 `src/ui/
` 组件" and "旧版 `src/ui/` 代码已删除或归档". But the city-builder files still 
have `export default`. This is not a blocking issue though, just a migration inc
onsistency.\n\n**Major issues:**\n\n1. **UIAlert hide() duration**: PRD-004 5.15
specifies 200ms for hide(), code uses 150ms (`UITweens.fade.duration`). The desi
gn-spec.md section 3.4 also says for UIAlert hide: `duration=200ms`.\n\n2. **UIT
oast dismiss() and UIAlert hide() use relative y drift**: `y: this.y - 10` inste
ad of `y: this.baseY - 10`. If called during an in-progress animation, the tween
target will be relative to current (mid-animation) y, causing cumulative drift o
n rapid show/hide cycles. The agent-design-guide.md explicitly warns about this:
"`show()` / `hide()` 动画基于当前状态做相对偏移 → 重复调用时坐标/透明度/缩放累积
漂移". This is explicitly listed as a common trap.\n\n3. **UIButton.setTexture()
calls setupInteraction() without removing old listeners**: Actually it destroys 
the old background and creates a new one, so old listeners are on the destroyed 
object. But there\'s another issue: `setTexture` doesn\'t update `this.label`\'s
reference properly? No, label is removed and re-added. The issue is that `setupI
nteraction()` adds listeners to `this.background`, and when `setTexture()` is ca
lled, it destroys the old background and creates a new one, then calls `setupInt
eraction()` again. The old listeners are on the destroyed object, so that\'s fin
e. But wait - `setTexture()` also calls `createBackground()` which sets `this.ba
ckground`, then `setupInteraction()` sets interactive on it. This seems okay.\n\
nActually, looking at `UIButton.setTexture()`:\n```typescript\n  setTexture(text
ure: string): void {\n    this.config.texture = texture;\n    this.background.de
stroy();\n    this.createBackground();\n    // Re-add label on top of background
\n    this.remove(this.label);\n    this.add(this.label);\n    this.setupInterac
