    think='Let me now compile all my findings and write the review report.\n\nKe
y observations:\n\n**Blocking issues:**\n1. **UIAlert `hide()` animation duratio
n violates PRD-004**: PRD-004 5.15 specifies hide duration=200ms, code uses `UIT
weens.fade.duration` (150ms).\n2. **UIToast `dismiss()` and UIAlert `hide()` use
relative y offset causing drift**: `y: this.y - 10` instead of `y: this.baseY - 
10`. This is explicitly warned against in `docs/frontend/agent-design-guide.md` 
as a common trap.\n3. **UIIcon `onClick` fires on tween `onComplete` instead of 
`pointerup`**: Inconsistent with UIButton and means click doesn\'t fire on relea
se but after animation. No `pointerupoutside` handling.\n\nWait, let me reconsid
er whether these are truly Blocking. The review framework says:\n> Blocking（阻
塞）：功能不可用、数据丢失、安全漏洞。必须修复后才能合并。\n> Major（严重）：影
响用户体验或维护性，建议修复。\n\nIssue 1 (duration mismatch) is a spec deviatio
n but doesn\'t make the function unusable. It should be Major.\nIssue 2 (y drift
) could cause visual bugs on rapid interactions but is an edge case. It should b
e Major.\nIssue 3 (UIIcon click behavior) affects user experience - clicks don\'
t register properly if the user releases early or moves away. This is more like 
Major.\n\nAre there any true Blocking issues? Let me think...\n\nThe PR touches 
`city-builder/ui/` files. If those changes break the game, that\'s Blocking. Let
me check if the `SceneSwitchBar.ts` changes are correct.\n\nOld API:\n```typescr
ipt\n{ id: SceneType.City, label: \'城建\' }\nselectedId: this.currentScene,\non
Select: (id) => this.switchScene(id as SceneType),\n```\n\nNew API:\n```typescri
pt\n{ key: SceneType.City, label: \'城建\' }\nselectedIndex: this.currentScene =
== SceneType.City ? 0 : 1,\nonChange: (key) => this.switchScene(key as SceneType
),\n```\n\nThis looks correct. `SceneType.City` and `SceneType.Battle` are strin
g enum values presumably, so `key` works.\n\nWait, there\'s a subtle issue. `sel
ectedIndex` expects a number (0 or 1), but `this.currentScene` is of type `Scene
Type` which is presumably a string enum. The old code used `selectedId: this.cur
rentScene` (string). The new code maps it to index: `selectedIndex: this.current
Scene === SceneType.City ? 0 : 1`. That\'s correct.\n\nThen `setCurrentScene(sce
neType: SceneType)` also does: `this.segmentedControl.setSelectedIndex(sceneType
=== SceneType.City ? 0 : 1)`. Correct.\n\nAnd the `onChange` callback: `onChange
: (key) => this.switchScene(key as SceneType)`. Since `key` is the string value 
from `SceneType`, this works.\n\nThe `emit(\'before-switch\')` fix:\n```typescri
pt\nconst listeners = this.listeners(\'before-switch\') as Array<(type: SceneTyp
e) => boolean>;\nconst canSwitch = listeners.length === 0 || listeners.every(fn 
=> fn(sceneType));\n```\nThis fixes the common trap about `emit()` return value.
Good.\n\nThe `TopInfoBar.ts` changes: The `UIAvatar` config now requires `textur
e: string`. The PR added `texture: \'\'` to satisfy this. But `fallbackText: \'
道\'` is still there. The UIAvatar now has different behavior when `texture: \'\
'` - it will use `createFallbackRect` or show fallback text. Let me check UIAvat
